The '''Grammarians of Basrah''' were grammarians and language scholars of Basra in the [[Islamic Golden Age]], who laid down the rules of grammar and of literary style, and whose teachings and writings became the canon of the [[Arabic language]].  Shortly after the school's foundation in Basra, a rival school was established in Kufa, by the '''[[Grammarians of Kufa]]'''.  The book ''Kitab al-Fihrist'' by the tenth century author, Ibn Ishaq al-Warraq, known as "[[Ibn Nadim|al-Nadim]]", provides biographical details of the leading figures  and is the principal source for early accounts of the two schools. The schools represent the two main branches in the development of Arabic grammar and punctuation, linguistics, [[philology]], Quranic exegesis and recital, [[Hadith]], poetry and literature.

==Founding & Most Celebrated Philologists==

*[[Abu al-Aswad al-Du'ali]] Ẓālim ibn Amr ibn Sufyān (c. 605-688 CE) originator of Arabic grammar and founder of Baṣrah school.  {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=662}}{{sfn|Dodge|loc=I|pp=87-91, 346}}

*[[Abu 'Amr ibn al-'Ala'|Abū 'Amr b. al-'Alā]] (689-770 CE), an eminent scholar and one of the seven readers of the Qur’ān, who burned his collections of old poetry, &c., to devote himself to religion. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=II|p=399}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=63-231}}
*[[al-Khalil ibn Ahmad|Khalīl ibn Aḥmad]], (c. 718-786 CE) inventor of the Arabic system of metres who wrote the first Arabic lexicon (al-Kitābu ‘l-’Ayn); incomplete on his death. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=493}}{{sfn|Nawawī|p=230}}
*[[Sibawayh|Sībawayh]] (d. 793/796 CE), the Persian whose Grammar, entitled 'The Book of Sībawayh,' is universally celebrated. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=II|p=396}}
*[[al-Asmai|al-Aṣma’ī]] (c. 739-833 CE) and [[Abu Ubaidah (scholar)|Abū 'Ubayda]](ca. 728-824), great humanists who flourished under [[Harun al-Rashid|Hārūn al-Rashid]] {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=II|p=123}}{{sfn|Nicholson|p=343}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=119-361}}
*[[al-Mubarrad]] (d. 899 CE), philologist best-known for Al-Kāmil {{sfn|Wright (1894)}} {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=III|p=31}}{{sfn|Yāqūt|loc=Irshad,VI(7)|p=137}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=76-398o}}
*[[al-Sukkari|al-Sukkarī]] (d. 889 CE), a collector and critic of old Arabian poetry and ancient tradition. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=IV|p=300 n.2}}{{sfn|Flügel|p=89}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=75-353}}
*[[Ibn Durayd]] (d. 934 CE), a distinguished philologist, genealogist, and poet, awarded a pension by caliph [[Al-Muqtadir]] for his contribution to science; principal works, his famous ode “The Maqṣūra,” a voluminous lexicon (al-'Jamhara fi ‘l-Lugha) and a treatise on the genealogies of the Arab tribes (Kitābu ‘l-Ishtiqāq). {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=III|p=37}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=78-191}}
*'Isa ibn 'Umar al-Thaqafi (d. 766/67 CE) blind, grammarian, Quran reciter, teacher of [[Sibawayh|Sībawayh]]: - ''The Compilation''; ''The Perfected'' (Completed). Both texts lost.{{sfn|Khallikān|loc=II|p=419}}
*[[Yunus ibn Habib]] (d. 798 CE) Persian, expert on gram. inflection, lived to be 88 years old; - ''Meaning of the Quran''; ''Languages'' (Vernaculars); ''The Large Book of Rare Forms'' [in the Qur'an]; ''Similes'' (Proverbs); ''The Small Book of Rare Forms''{{sfn|Khallikān|loc=VI|p=586}}{{sfn|Dodge|loc=I|pp=63-158}}*[[Al-Khalil ibn Ahmad al-Farahidi|al-Khalīl ibn Aḥmad]], Abd al-Rahman.  (c. 718-786 CE); first lexicographer of Arabic, derived points of grammar and developed prosody rules: - ''[[Kitab al-Ayn]]'' {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=493}}{{sfn|Nawawī|p=230}}
*[[Al-Jarmi|Al-Jarmī Abū ‘Umar Ṣāliḥ ibn Isḥāq]], (d. 840 CE) grammarian, student of [[al-Akhfash al-Awsat|al-Akhfash]], [[Sa'id ibn Aws al-Ansari|Abū Zayd]], [[Al-Asma'i]] and others, who taught [[al-Kitab of Sibawayh|al-Kitab]] to [[al-Tawwazi]] and debated in Baghdād.{{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=629}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=123-125, 128, 137, 139, 188, 1023}}

