{{Infobox scientist |name = Timothy Lee Barnwell |image = Barnwell portrait.jpg |image_size = 250px |caption = Tim Barnwell with 4x5 [[view camera]] in the field. |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|2|17}} |birth_place = Bryson City NC, U.S. |residence = Asheville, North Carolina, U.S. |field = [[Documentary photography]], [[Fine-art photography]], [[Commercial photography]] |alma_mater = [[University of North Carolina at Asheville]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|AB]])</small> |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = [[Walker Evans]], [[Ansel Adams]], [[Arnold Newman]], [[George Tice]] |influenced = |prizes = |footnotes = }}
'''Timothy Lee Barnwell''' (born February 17, 1955) is an American author, commercial photographer, and [[fine art]] photographer based in Asheville, NC.<ref>The Village Voice(Print), Feb. 21, 1984,</ref> He has worked as a photojournalist and had images published in numerous publications including Time, Newsweek, Mother Jones, Billboard, LensWork, National Parks, American Craft, Astronomy, Outdoor Photographer, and B&W magazine. In 1981 he founded Appalachian Photographic Workshops and served as Director and photography instructor until in closed in 1988. He is the author of five books, The Face of Appalachia: Portraits from the Mountain Farm (W.W. Norton/NY, 2003); On Earth's Furrowed Brow: The Appalachian Farm in Photographs (W.W. Norton/NY, 2007); Hands in Harmony: Traditional Crafts and Music in Appalachia (W.W. Norton/NY, 2009); Blue Ridge Parkway Vistas: A Comprehensive Identification Guide to What You See From the Many Overlooks (Numinous Editions,2014),and Great Smoky Mountains Vistas: A Guide, with Mountain Peak Identifications, for What to See and Do In and Around the National Park (Numinous Editions, 2016).
==Bibliography== *''[[The Face of Appalachia]]: Portraits from the Mountain Farm'' (2003)<ref>{{cite web|last=MacNeille|first=Suzanne|title=BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION; An Eye on Appalachia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/29/books/books-in-brief-nonfiction-an-eye-on-appalachia.html|publisher=NYT|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Walpole|first=Peter|title=The Face of Appalachia: Portraits from the Mountain Farm (review)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-662696231.html|accessdate=26 January 2014|newspaper=The Virginia Quarterly Review|date=July 1, 2004}}</ref> *''On Earth's Furrowed Brow: The Appalachian Farm in Photographs'' (2007) *''[[Hands in Harmony]]: Portraits from the Mountain Farm'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|title=Hands in Harmony: Traditional Crafts and Music in Appalachia by Tim Barnwell|url=http://www.ourstate.com/hands-in-harmony-by-tim-barnwell/|publisher=Our State|accessdate=26 January 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228045830/http://www.ourstate.com/hands-in-harmony-by-tim-barnwell/|archivedate=28 December 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=HANDS IN HARMONY: TRADITIONAL CRAFTS AND MUSIC IN APPALACHIA (review)|url=http://bluegrassmusic.com/content/reviews/reviews-may-2010/book-review-hands-in-harmony-traditional-crafts-and-music-in-applachia-tim-barnwell/|publisher=Bluegrass Music Magazine|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>
==Exhibitions== Barnwell's photography has been included in over 65 exhibits since 1977, including three one-man shows in New York City's SOHO Photo Gallery. His work is included in the permanent collections of numerous museums such as the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web|title="Dinosaur", Port Clyde, Maine Tim Barnwell (American, born 1955)|url=http://metmuseum.org/Collections/search-the-collections/263410?vid=ab00b9e9-7a4b-4b4f-b961-d54dd4a4b531|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> the [[Asheville Art Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Barnwell|url=http://www.ashevilleart.org/artists/timbarnwell/|publisher=Ashville Art Museum|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> the [[Newark Museum of Art]], the New Orleans Museum of Art, and the High Museum.
